{
  "text": "A more inventive method for forming a porous framework is the direct assembly of transition metal ions via a bottom-up approach, particularly using polyoxometalates (POMs) as cluster precursors 13 . There are only a few examples of zeolitic transition metal oxides. The typical materials are porous frameworks based on ring-shaped [P 8 W 48 O 184 ] unit [CITATION_1] 15 , [MnV 13 O 38 ] unit 16 , and pentagon [Mo 6 O 21 ] units 17 . However, the current materials suffer from problems that include poor structural diversity, unopened micropores 18 , and low surface area and porosity [CITATION_2] 19 . Therefore, new progresses in obtaining zeolitic materials with all-transition metal oxides that would increase the diversity of material design are strongly desired by material scientists.",
